<br>
A man plays a game because he has a competitive spirit. He enjoys excelling at something. He enjoys beating other players, or being beaten and striving to win next time.<br>
<br>
Women, I think, play games more for the social element. They enjoy sitting around the card table, chatting with friends, drinking coffee and laughing at their husbands trying to mercilessly one-up each other.<br>
<br>
Computer games typically only appeal to men, because they are sitting by themselves at the keyboard, trying to beat their opponent, be it the CPU or some other player over the internet. Like Quake, for instance. The social element is completely gone, so women don't find this kind of gaming attractive. It may be that your wife or girlfriend considers all games to be the same, having classified them as &quot;not fun&quot; years ago.<br>
<br>
If we continue to use Quake as an example, also consider the level of skill Quake 3 requires you to have before you can be competitive. You need to lightning reflexes, practice, and having a lot of past experience helps too. You aren't born knowing that this box increases your health or this box increases your ammo. These are things you learn, and while a lot of men may already have this knowledge from playing previous games, a woman who has never played a computer game would probably find learning Quake 3 to be an almost insurmountable task, and the rewords certainly wouldn't justify the effort.<br>
<br>
The very first computer game I ever saw my wife take an interest in was Warcraft 2. You see, at the office where I work, we are a fairly tight-knit group of friends. It's very common for us to pick up the latest multiplayer game and play over the LAN. We can talk to each other this way, so there is a lot of good natured taunting and such. Additionally, Warcraft didn't require the kind of frenetic skills and instincts that a game like Quake needed. So my wife joined us one game, and immediately enjoyed it. She liked the funny things the units would say, and she treated the game almost like SimCity, just sitting there building up while everybody else would hack away at each other. Since she played so non-combatively, we always left her alone as a non-threat until the very last. She never won, but she had fun.<br>
<br>
Finally that brings us to Everquest. I have never seen a game that would be more potentially appealing to women players. The entire thing is an environment geared towards social interaction. There is no real &quot;win&quot; or &quot;lose&quot; situation. You just go out and explore, see what's there. The game is VERY forgiving at the start. You don't get into a fight unless you want to in a newbie zone. You are free to wander around and talk to NPCs or whatever. Plus it is a fantasy environment, and my wife enjoys reading fantasy novels, unicorns, dragons, and suchlike.<br>
<br>
But I ramble on too much. As you can see, I've given a lot of thought to the subject and enjoy discussing it. But if your wife/girlfriend enjoys games of any sort she would probably enjoy Everquest. It sounds like she is already predisposed against computer games as a whole. How you can break such a predisposition is not for me to say. But I know that the most important step is for her to really <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> look</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> at what you're doing and say &quot;Hey, that looks like a lot of fun.&quot;<br>
<br>
